<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="stakeholder-management">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-operations</domain>
    <summary>Map stakeholders on Power/Interest grid with explicit attitude, assign named owner and engagement cadence per stakeholder, codify approval gates for agent-enforced sign-off.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>stakeholder</tag>
      <tag>engagement</tag>
      <tag>management</tag>
      <tag>communication</tag>
      <tag>relationships</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>stakeholder</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Stakeholder Management</title>
    <summary>Stakeholder management identifies everyone affected by a product (end users, decision makers, influencers, builders, support, external), maps them on a Power/Interest grid with an explicit attitude column (Supporter/Neutral/Resistor), assigns a named owner and engagement cadence per stakeholder, and codifies approval gates so agents can block SDD transitions until named approvers sign off.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Products fail due to stakeholder misalignment, not technology — silent resistors in the "Manage Closely" quadrant kill projects without appearing in any risk log. A Power/Interest grid without the attitude dimension is a 2D map of a 3D problem. Forcing one named owner per relationship and a concrete cadence (not "ad-hoc") converts a ceremony document into an executable engagement plan.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Cross-functional product launch with 5+ named stakeholders where misalignment has already cost time once.</item>
        <item>Re-org or PM handover: dump every stakeholder relationship into a register so the incoming PM can start without rediscovery.</item>
        <item>Roadmap quarter start: refresh the grid, decide which stakeholders move from Inform to Partner for upcoming bets.</item>
        <item>An SDD feature has a named approval gate (legal, security, head of sales) — codify it so the executor agent blocks until the approver signs off.</item>
        <item>Building a multi-agent comms pipeline where status-bot, release-notes-bot, and executive-summary-bot all pull audience from a shared register.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solo founder pre-revenue with only customers and family — a 5-line note in the project README is sufficient.</item>
        <item>Internal dev-tools used by under 10 engineers in the same Slack channel — async stand-up + RFC comments cover it.</item>
        <item>Crisis/incident mode: run incident-management first, restore service, update the register post-mortem.</item>
        <item>When the problem is "we don't know who's doing what work" — use raci-matrix or WBS, not this.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Stakeholder Types">
      <list>
        <item>End Users: customers, employees — need value from product.</item>
        <item>Decision Makers: executives, sponsors — need business outcomes.</item>
        <item>Influencers: advisors, thought leaders — need credibility and early access.</item>
        <item>Builders: developers, designers — need clear requirements.</item>
        <item>Support: customer success, sales — need product knowledge.</item>
        <item>External: partners, regulators — need compliance and compatibility.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Power/Interest Grid">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always add an explicit attitude column (Supporter / Neutral / Resistor) to the Power/Interest grid. Mark Unknown when attitude cannot be inferred from a cited source. Never leave attitude blank.</statement>
        <rationale>A Power/Interest grid without the attitude dimension is a 2D map of a 3D problem. A high-power stakeholder coded as "Manage Closely" but secretly a Resistor is the silent killer of cross-functional product launches.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>High Power, High Interest → Manage Closely: engage deeply, regular bidirectional updates, co-creation where possible.</item>
        <item>High Power, Low Interest → Keep Satisfied: periodic updates, frame in terms of business outcomes, not details.</item>
        <item>Low Power, High Interest → Keep Informed: involve in feedback sessions, one-way updates are sufficient for most.</item>
        <item>Low Power, Low Interest → Monitor: minimal effort, periodic check-ins only.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Engagement Levels">
      <list>
        <item>Partner: active collaboration, co-creation, regular meetings, bidirectional input loops.</item>
        <item>Involved: regular input, reviews, feedback sessions.</item>
        <item>Informed: one-way updates, newsletters, demos.</item>
        <item>Monitor: minimal contact, periodic check-ins.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Every stakeholder must have a named engagement cadence (weekly 1:1, biweekly email, monthly review). "Ad-hoc" is code for "nothing happens".</statement>
        <rationale>A communication plan without a concrete cadence produces the same outcome as no plan — stakeholders feel ignored, resistors go undetected, and late-stage blockers emerge at critical milestones.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Four-Step Process">
      <list>
        <item>Step 1 — Identify: who uses, pays, approves, builds, supports, or could block this product.</item>
        <item>Step 2 — Analyze: what they want, what they fear, power level, interest level, attitude.</item>
        <item>Step 3 — Plan engagement: cadence, format, information they need, relationship owner.</item>
        <item>Step 4 — Execute and adapt: regular touchpoints, track attitude shifts, handle conflicts proactively.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Stakeholder Register Schema">
      <rule>
        <statement>The register must include these columns: name, role, interest (H/M/L), power (H/M/L), attitude (Supporter/Neutral/Resistor/Unknown), engagement level (Partner/Involved/Informed/Monitor), owner. The owner column is non-optional — "whole team manages this exec" means nobody does.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a named owner per stakeholder relationship, escalations have no clear path and engagement drifts to whoever is most available rather than most informed.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cite the source for every Power and Attitude classification (meeting notes, org chart, repo CODEOWNERS). Mark Unknown if no source exists, not a guess.</statement>
        <rationale>LLM-generated stakeholder analyses hallucinate stakeholders from project-type templates. Requiring a source for each classification catches fabricated rows before they drive engagement decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Communication Plan Matrix">
      <list>
        <item>Executive sponsor: status + decisions, weekly, 1:1 meeting, PM owns.</item>
        <item>Dev team: requirements + changes, daily, stand-up, PM owns.</item>
        <item>Sales team: features + timeline, bi-weekly, email update, PM owns.</item>
        <item>Customers: releases + feedback, monthly, newsletter, Marketing owns.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Define the escalation path with real names and backups: Issue → PM → (24h unresolved) → Director → (48h unresolved) → Executive sponsor. "Escalate to Director" with no name is unactionable at 11pm.</statement>
        <rationale>Escalation paths with role names instead of person names fail when roles turn over or when multiple people hold the role. Named individuals with backup contacts are actionable; role labels are not.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Worked Examples">
      <example type="good">
        <note>SaaS feature launch (5+ stakeholders): CEO (High/Medium → Keep Satisfied, quarterly), Head of Sales (High/High → Partner, weekly sync), Engineering Lead (Medium/High → Involved, daily standups), Key Customer (Low/High → Informed, beta access), Support Team (Low/High → Involved, training sessions). Explicit owner assigned to each row.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Solo product stakeholder register: Early customers (need working product and support → Discord and email), Payment processor (need compliance → documentation), Hosting provider (need technical requirements → support tickets), Advisor/mentor (need progress → monthly call), Family (need time boundaries → clear schedule). Even solopreneurs have stakeholders requiring explicit engagement plans.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>Register with attitude column left blank for all rows, owner column filled with "team", and cadence listed as "ad-hoc". This register produces no value — attitude Unknown rows never get escalated, no one owns relationships, and "ad-hoc" means nothing happens.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow">
      <p>Drive stakeholder management as a 3-loop pipeline. (1) Discovery loop: faion-pm-agent (or product-manager subagent) interviews the team and outputs a draft stakeholder-register.md into .aidocs/product_docs/. (2) Engagement loop: a status-update agent reads the register, generates audience-tailored updates (executive summary vs. dev daily vs. customer newsletter), and routes via the configured channel adapters. (3) Drift-detection loop: weekly cron-driven agent diffs new stakeholder mentions in meeting notes / Slack export against the register and flags additions or attitude shifts for human review. Critical: the register is read by many agents, written by one (or by humans). Treat it like a config file with a clear owner.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents:</p>
      <list>
        <item>faion-pm-agent — runs Step 1–2 of the framework: identify, analyze, draft engagement plan. Outputs to .aidocs/product_docs/stakeholder-register.md.</item>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — wraps stakeholder-related SDD tasks ("F-053: Get legal sign-off on data-export feature"); enforces that the named stakeholder from the register is captured as task approver and blocks done transition until sign-off is logged.</item>
        <item>password-scrubber-agent — run before committing any register or comms-plan artifact: strip or hash PII before the file lands in a public repo.</item>
        <item>faion-marketing-manager (sibling skill) — consumes the register's external segment (customers, advisors, partners) to drive newsletter and announcement sequencing. Don't duplicate customer lists — link.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Discovery Prompt">
      <p>Input: project brief at .aidocs/product_docs/project-brief.md + team-list at .aidocs/team.md. Task: Build stakeholder register. For each candidate stakeholder, populate columns: name, role, interest (H/M/L), power (H/M/L), attitude (Supporter/Neutral/Resistor — mark Unknown if you cannot infer), engagement level (Partner/Involved/Informed/Monitor), owner. Cite the source line for every Power and Attitude classification (no inference without source). Mark any stakeholder with attitude=Unknown for human follow-up. Output as a single markdown table to .aidocs/product_docs/stakeholder-register.md.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Engagement Plan Prompt">
      <p>Read .aidocs/product_docs/stakeholder-register.md. For each stakeholder where engagement is at least Involved, generate a one-line message draft for this week's update, tailored to their (power, interest, attitude) cell. Resistors get a separate "concern + mitigation" message. Do not send; output to a draft file for human review.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Register Health Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Tie register review to the same cadence as roadmap review (quarterly minimum). Never let the PM update the register unilaterally — refresh as a 30-minute team meeting so others can flag attitude shifts the PM misses.</statement>
        <rationale>Register rot is the most common failure: a doc built at kick-off stays unchanged while the exec sponsor leaves, attitudes shift, and new blockers emerge. Team review catches changes no single person sees.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Maintain a "former stakeholders" archive, not just the current list. When someone moves on, record exit and reason — never delete the row. Future PMs need the context.</statement>
        <rationale>Stakeholder history informs future relationship-building. Knowing why a previous exec became a resistor prevents repeating the same mistake with their successor.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Pair the register with a decision log. Each Partner-tier stakeholder must appear in the decision log monthly or be downgraded. Engagement that does not produce decisions is theater.</statement>
        <rationale>A stakeholder coded as "Partner" but absent from decision records is actually receiving "Inform"-level engagement. The decision log makes the gap visible before the relationship deteriorates.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Safety Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Never let an agent autonomously change a stakeholder's engagement level from Partner to Informed. Changing someone's engagement level is a relationship downgrade with political consequences. Agent suggests, human approves.</statement>
        <rationale>Automated downgrade of a Partner-tier stakeholder to Informed can read as a snub or signal of project de-prioritization. The consequences are relationship damage that cannot be undone with a follow-up email.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Run password-scrubber-agent or equivalent before committing any register or comms-plan artifact. Registers contain personal contact details, internal email addresses, sometimes phone numbers. Never let a register land in a public repo without scrubbing.</statement>
        <rationale>PII leakage via stakeholder registers is a GDPR and internal-trust risk. Agents push to git and it becomes public without a scrubbing step.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>For external/customer stakeholders, separate the register from any marketing CRM. Cross-link by ID, never duplicate contact data.</statement>
        <rationale>Duplicated customer lists in the register and CRM drift out of sync. When opt-out status changes in the CRM, the unlinked register continues to drive communications to opted-out users.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Failure Modes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM hallucinating stakeholders that "should" exist for a project type ("Compliance Officer", "Data Privacy Lead") without a source.</description>
        <reason>Require the model to cite an actual source — meeting notes, org chart, CODEOWNERS — before adding a row. Hallucinated stakeholders lead to wasted engagement cycles on non-existent relationships.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Models defaulting to Supporter for attitude when asked "is this exec a supporter?" because of sycophantic training.</description>
        <reason>Force the model to mark Unknown unless evidence is cited; the stakeholder-lint.py script enforces this at commit time. Unknown attitudes must be resolved through 1:1 conversation, not LLM inference.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Power/interest classifications inferred from title alone in a matrix org where a "Senior Manager" has more real influence than a "VP".</description>
        <reason>Feed actual org-chart text or interview snippets rather than job titles. Title-based classification is wrong in consensus-driven and matrix orgs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cron-driven weekly stakeholder sentiment scan of Slack messages auto-escalating on mis-classified Resistor signals.</description>
        <reason>Queue sentiment findings for human review, never auto-escalate. A false Resistor classification triggering an escalation can damage a relationship the system was meant to protect.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Long-context dumps of the full register into every agent prompt, wasting tokens and leaking PII to downstream agents.</description>
        <reason>Pass only the relevant slice (one quadrant, or one engagement tier) to each agent. The register as a whole is a program-management artifact, not an agent context blob.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Limitations and Failure Modes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Register rot: the doc is built once at project kick-off and never updated.</description>
        <reason>By month 3, the named exec sponsor has left the company and the register still drives the weekly update email. Tie register review to the same cadence as roadmap review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Power/interest grids hide attitude: a high-power stakeholder coded as "Manage Closely" but secretly a Resistor.</description>
        <reason>Always carry an explicit attitude column (Supporter / Neutral / Resistor) and color it. Attitude is the third dimension the grid cannot show.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Communication-plan theatre: an elaborate matrix that nobody actually executes.</description>
        <reason>If the PM isn't running the weekly sync the matrix promises, the matrix is a lie. Reduce cadence to what will actually happen.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Over-engagement of Low Power, Low Interest stakeholders out of politeness.</description>
        <reason>Burns PM cycles and dilutes signal. The whole point of the grid is to deprioritize. Manage this quadrant with periodic check-ins, not active engagement.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>One-way "stakeholder updates" treated as engagement: a newsletter is information, not engagement.</description>
        <reason>Engagement requires bidirectional input loops (decisions, feedback, escalation paths). Frame updates as such, not as engagement substitutes.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cross-cultural blind spots: Power is more diffuse in matrix orgs and consensus-driven cultures.</description>
        <reason>A simple grid encodes a Western-corporate hierarchy assumption. Annotate, don't auto-trust. Feed actual org-chart data instead of inferring from titles.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Carry an explicit attitude column. Power/interest grids without attitude are 2D maps of a 3D problem; resistors hidden in the Manage Closely quadrant kill projects.</item>
        <item>One owner per stakeholder relationship. "Whole team manages this exec" means nobody does. The owner column is non-optional.</item>
        <item>Every stakeholder has a named engagement cadence (weekly 1:1, biweekly email, monthly review). "Ad-hoc" is code for "nothing happens".</item>
        <item>Pair the register with a decision log. Engagement that doesn't produce decisions is theatre. Each Partner-tier stakeholder should appear in the decision log monthly or be downgraded.</item>
        <item>Negative space matters: maintain a "former stakeholders" archive, not just a current list. When someone moves on, don't delete — record exit and reason. Future PMs need that context.</item>
        <item>Tie escalation paths to real names and backups. "Escalate to Director" with no name is unactionable at 11pm.</item>
        <item>For external/customer stakeholders, separate the register from any marketing CRM. Treat the register as program-management metadata; let the CRM hold the relationship history. Cross-link by ID, don't duplicate.</item>
        <item>Refresh quarterly with the team in a 30-min meeting; do not let the PM update unilaterally. Other people see attitudes the PM misses.</item>
        <item>Pair this methodology with raci-matrix (responsibility) and roadmap-design (timing). The trio answers Who / What-they-do / When.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/stakeholder-register.md" purpose="Register with name/role/interest/power/attitude/engagement/owner columns and detailed profile section"/>
      <template path="templates/communication-plan.md" purpose="Communication matrix, key messages by audience, escalation path"/>
      <template path="templates/meeting-template.md" purpose="Stakeholder update meeting agenda: progress, decisions needed, risks, action items"/>
      <template path="templates/stakeholder-lint.py" purpose="Lint register for rot patterns: unknown attitudes, missing owners, high-power under-engagement"/>
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.pmi.org/learning/library">PMI Pulse of the Profession: Stakeholder Engagement</link>
      <link href="https://www.atlassian.com/work-management/project-management/stakeholder-analysis">Atlassian Stakeholder Analysis Guide</link>
      <ref slug="raci-matrix"/>
      <ref slug="roadmap-design"/>
      <ref slug="business-analysis-planning"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
